Random Forest flows on the cloud

One of the killer features of Metaflow is that Data Scientists Don't Need to Know Kubernetes with Metaflow, or the ins-and-outs of any compute platform for that matter, but they can still benefit from the power that modern distributed computing systems afford.

To get started right away, run this command and then read through this panel as the cloud workflow gets going:
python flows/cloud/rf_flow_cloud.py --environment=conda run --with kubernetes

Running remote tasks helps us scale ML workflows in development and in production.

Running tasks remotely is also a great way to ensure your environments are reproducible, which is very important in production systems.

Why @conda and --with environment=conda?

The astute Metaflow will see that we are packaging dependencies for each workflow step in @conda decorators. This is a great way to manage versions of packages your workflow code depends on. This is important when running steps on remote machines, especially since common ML dependencies are unlikely to be installed by default on those machines.

Run all tasks in a flow remotely

To do this, we modify the Metaflow run command using --with kubernetes:
python flows/cloud/rf_flow_cloud.py --environment=conda run --with kubernetes


Run some tasks remotely, and some locally

To run some tasks remotely, and some locally, you can use the @kubernetes decorator, which also allows you to define different resources for each task, such as memory and the number of (virtual) cpu.
